\@LN{268}{4}
\@LN{269}{4}
\@LN{270}{4}
\@LN{271}{4}
\@LN{272}{4}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces  Telluric correction applied to the OH-cleaned spectra. The figure shows the spectra after division by an empirically derived telluric template, highlighting the removal of atmospheric absorption features, in particular the O$_2$ B band around 690\,nm and the O$_2$ A band near 760\,nm. The correction preserves the overall spectral shape while reducing the impact of atmospheric absorption, enabling more accurate flux measurements across the full wavelength range. }}{6}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:telluric}{{10}{6}{}{figure.10}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {11}{\ignorespaces  Validation of the flux calibration using external photometric measurements. The calibrated spectra are compared to broad-band photometric fluxes from the SkyMapper survey, demonstrating good agreement within the expected uncertainties. This confirms the reliability of the absolute flux scaling and the preservation of the spectral energy distribution across the observed wavelength range. }}{6}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:fluxcal}{{11}{6}{}{figure.11}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {12}{\ignorespaces  Step08 wavelength-attachment and alignment diagnostics. Normalized spectra from all slits are overplotted in the wavelength region of the O$_2$ A band after wavelength vectors have been attached to the extracted one-dimensional spectra. The close alignment of the telluric absorption feature across slits demonstrates the internal consistency of the wavelength assignment prior to the OH-subtraction and telluric-correction stages. }}{6}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:step08_qc}{{12}{6}{}{figure.12}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {13}{\ignorespaces  OH emission modeling and subtraction for the full set of extracted spectra. Each panel shows a one-dimensional spectrum as a function of wavelength, illustrating the dense forest of atmospheric emission lines and their removal by the pipeline. The subtraction is performed using an iterative, locally constrained Gaussian modeling of emission features combined with a two-pass continuum estimation. The resulting spectra show a strong suppression of sky emission lines while preserving the continuum and astrophysical features, with no evidence of systematic oversubtraction. }}{6}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:step09_qc}{{13}{6}{}{figure.13}{}}
\@LN@col{1}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {14}{\ignorespaces  Telluric correction applied to the OH-cleaned spectra. The spectra are shown after division by an empirically derived telluric template, highlighting the removal of atmospheric absorption features, in particular the O$_2$ B band around 690\,nm and the O$_2$ A band near 760\,nm. The correction preserves the overall spectral shape while reducing the impact of atmospheric absorption, enabling accurate flux measurements across the full wavelength range. }}{7}{}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:telluric}{{14}{7}{}{figure.14}{}}
